05869nam a22008055i 9780813537849DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20052005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135378497 a10.36019/97808135378492doi  a(DE-B1597)529919  a(OCoLC)228171102  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a333.911 aRoth, Dik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiquid Relations :bContested Water Rights and Legal Complexity /cMargreet Zwarteveen, Rutgerd Boelens, Dik Roth. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tABBREVIATIONS -- t1. Legal Complexity in the Analysis of Water Rights and Water Resources Management -- t2. Prescribing Gender Equity? The Case of the Tukucha Nala Irrigation System, Central Nepal -- t3. Defending Indigenous Water Rights with the Laws of a Dominant Culture -- t4. In the Shadow of Uniformity -- t5. Anomalous Water Rights and the Politics of Normalization -- t6. Complexities of Water Governance -- t7. Special Law -- t8. A Win-Some Lose-All Game -- t9. Redressing Racial Inequities through Water Law in South Africa -- t10. Routes to Water Rights -- t11. Analyzing Water Rights, Multiple Uses, and Intersectoral Water Transfers -- t12. Water Rights and Legal Pluralism -- tREFERENCES -- tNOTES ON THE CONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWater management plays an increasingly critical role in national and international policy agendas. Growing scarcity, overuse, and pollution, combined with burgeoning demand, have made socio-political and economic conflicts almost unavoidable. Proposals to address water shortages are usually based on two key assumptions: (1) water is a commodity that can be bought and sold and (2) “states,” or other centralized entities, should control access to water. Liquid Relations criticizes these assumptions from a socio-legal perspective. Eleven case studies examine laws, distribution, and irrigation in regions around the world, including the United States, Nepal, Indonesia, Chile, Ecuador, India, and South Africa. In each case, problems are shown to be both ecological and human-made. The essays also consider the ways that gender, ethnicity, and class differences influence water rights and control. In the concluding chapter, the editors draw on the essays’ findings to offer an alternative approach to water rights and water governance issues. By showing how issues like water scarcity and competition are embedded in specific resource use and management histories, this volume highlights the need for analyses and solutions that are context-specific rather than universal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aWater rights. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh1 aBallabh, Vishwa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoelens, Rutgerd, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBoelens, Rutgerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruns, Bryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGentes, Ingo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGetches, David H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGil, Armando Guevara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeinzen-Dick, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPradhan, Rajendra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrakash, Anjal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1